<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n35275a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n35" href="#n35275a">N35 (VI.B.24)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n35all.htm#n35275a"> 275(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Isoud daughter / to Anguish</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The tower before mentioned under the name of Isod&apos;s-tower, together with Chape-lizod, a village near the city, (and the same may be said of Isod&apos;s fort in the Park), are reported by an historian &ldquo;to have taken their names from La-Beal-Isoud, or the fair Isoud, daughter to Anguish (I know not what) King of Ireland, and that the tower was a castle of pleasure for the kings to recreate themselves in.&rdquo; <small> J. Warburton, Rev. J. Whitelaw, and Rev. R. Walsh, <a name="WWWH" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WWWH"><cite title="source">A History of the City of Dublin</cite></a> (1818) 70</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
